abstract = {Chemical biomass exergy (bioexergy) analysis is a powerful method for evaluating the efficiency and sustainability of biomass energy systems, focusing on elemental composition (C, H, O, N, and S). This review synthesizes insights from 101 studies, emphasizing exergy analysis applied to thermochemical processes with high exergy efficiencies: torrefaction (≥80 %), pyrolysis (52–98 %), and gasification (44–88.26 %). The ratio of chemical bioexergy to calorific value ranges from 1.013 to 1.078, indicating that calorific value alone underestimates the usable energy content by 1.3–7.8 %. Biomass fuels present unique challenges due to heterogeneous composition and complex conversion pathways, requiring precise data and thermodynamic understanding. Despite these difficulties, bioexergy analysis identifies irreversibilities and inefficiencies, aiding in the optimization of conversion processes and resource utilization. By clarifying thermodynamic fundamentals and demonstrating their practical relevance, this study contributes to the development of cleaner, more efficient biomass technologies aligned with circular economy principles.}
}
