abstract = {Hydrophobic interaction is one of the fundamental and critical driving forces in water for many biological activities such as the folding of enzymes and for many chemical phenomena such as the self-assembly of micelles. The development of organic synthesis in water is of paramount importance from both the economic and environmental points of view. To that end, the solubility issue of most organic reagents and the catalytic performance issue of molecular catalysts need to be tackled. Inspired by enzymes, the immobilization of molecular catalysts into organic colloids provides access to the implementation of organic catalytic synthesis in water. Furthermore, the hydrophobic interaction-assisted immobilization of molecular catalysts creates hydrophobic microenvironments, provides pseudo-solvent effects, and enables the compartmentalization of incompatible catalysts. In this review, we review the recent advances in the hydrophobic interaction-assisted immobilization of molecular catalysts into organic colloids. Three types of techniques, including self-assembly of amphiphiles, mixing-induced nanoprecipitation, and miniemulsion polymerization, have been recently utilized for the construction of these catalysts. Their preparation, characterization, and applications are summarized and discussed. The design principles, positive effects, and structure-activity relationships of these organic colloids will stimulate the development of more sustainable chemical processes and more efficient enzyme mimics.}
