abstract = {This chapter describes the digital health maturity metamodel (DHM3), its operationalization as the Digital Health Profile & Maturity Assessment Toolkit (DHPMAT), and the co-creation methodology to ensure relevance, ownership, and social capital in the local community. The metamodel approach unifies digital health and integrates existing domain-specific maturity models. The five foundations (ICT and IoT infrastructure, Digital tools, Health information sharing, Enablers of trust, and Quality Improvement) are assessed at five maturity stages based on system performance and information sharing extent and quality. DHM3 asserts that all interventions, policies, and programs must advance the digital health maturity (DHM) and Quintuple Aim simultaneously. The DHPMAT systematically assesses DHM across the micro (individual), meso (organization), macro (national health system), and meta (global) levels of the enterprise. DHM stages are grounded on Stage 3 (Standardized), where the deliverable is an enterprise architecture and platform compliant with interoperability standards and quality benchmarks for data, tools, systems, and services. DHM stages are stable and managed, but the processes are dynamic, evolving nonlinearly due to intrinsic (e.g., digital assets, creators, and users) and extrinsic factors (e.g., geopolitics, priorities, and opportunities).}
