author = {Miao Tian and Ye Han and Zhuo Zhang and Suyan Liu},
keywords = {Thermal hazards, Air gap, Protective clothing, Stored energy, CFD},
abstract = {Thermal protective clothing (TPC) and the air gap (AG) beneath it protect human skin during the heating phase by insulating and storing heat. However, during the cooling phase, the stored heat can become a secondary source, potentially causing thermal damage to the skin. In this study, a three-dimensional coupled heat transfer model was developed for a TPC system with a vertical AG. Indices were proposed to quantitatively evaluate the thermal protective and hazardous effects of the TPC and AG on the human body. Results showed that air density was crucial to the heat transfer mechanism within the AG. Compared with a temperature-dependent thermal conductivity, assuming a constant value for air (0.025–0.035 W/(m·K)) overestimated its protective performance. The thickness of the AG was directly related to non-uniform skin thermal injury (spatial variation in skin damage across different vertical positions). During the heating phase, airflow within the 6.4 mm AG remained steady, producing a uniform laminar distribution. In contrast, inward helical flow (a spiral circulation where air moved upward and inward, cooled near the skin surface, and recirculated downward toward the fabric) was observed in the 12 mm and 18 mm AGs. In the cooling phase, larger AGs released less stored heat to the skin. Increasing AG thickness from 6.4 mm to 18 mm not only improved thermal protection during exposure but also reduced skin heat absorption during the cooling phase by up to 14 %. Skin surface heat absorption was influenced by both AG thickness and height. These findings clarified the distinct thermal roles of the fabric and the AG during both heating and cooling phases, highlighting the AG's dual function in insulating against external heat and reducing residual heat release to the skin. The results provided theoretical support for optimizing AG thickness beneath TPC to reduce the risk of delayed skin burns.}
}
