abstract = {Photocatalytic conversion of flue gas-derived CO2 promotes sustainable carbon cycles, where interfacial-engineered catalysts address critical challenges in CO2 capture/activation and charge transfer dynamics under low-concentration environments. Here, Ag/TiO2-x Schottky junctions with dual hydrophilic/CO2-philic interfaces were engineered through oxygen vacancy (VO)-mediated work function modulation and site-selective polydopamine (PDA)/ortho-aminobenzenethiol (o-ABT) modification. This architecture synergistically activates H2O oxidation and CO2 capture/activation, enabling efficient dilute CO2-to-CO conversion in gas-solid photoreduction systems. The optimized o-ABT@Ag/TiO2-x@PDA (o-AATP) achieves 271.2 μmol g−1 h−1 CO yield under 20 % CO2 atmosphere, surpassing pure CO2 conditions (256.3 μmol g−1 h−1) with 48.4-fold enhancement over pristine TiO2-x. Significantly, o-AATP retained > 99.1 % selectivity and stable performance throughout 30–5 % CO2 concentrations, highlighting exceptional adaptability to dilute CO2 atmospheres. Multi-scale studies combining in situ diffuse reflectance infrared Fourier transform spectroscopy (DRIFTS), molecular dynamics (MD) simulations, and density functional theory (DFT) calculations reveal that PDA coating and Vo synergistically enhance H2O dissociation on TiO2-x. The Ag−S anchored o-ABT ligand aligns the amino group to form N−H···OCO hydrogen bonds with CO2, enabling concurrent CO2 capture and activation. The hydrophilic/CO2-philic interface engineering and synergistic redox modulation achieve 3.91 % apparent quantum yield (AQY) under 20 % CO2 atmosphere, demonstrating enhanced photocatalytic conversion performance for solar-driven industrial emission treatment.}
}
